`callbBackFunction` is executed before `map` runs and is actually returning the function inside of it. That function doesn&#39;t execute until `map` is fired, in which you can see it has the same function signature as `map`&#39;s callback.

```
function callbBackFunction() {        
    return (col, ind) =&gt; a.map(row =&gt; row[ind]);
}
```

Here&#39;s an example to help this make a bit more sense:
```
const fn1 = () =&gt; {
     return (name) =&gt; &quot;hello &quot; + name
}

// fn1 returns the name func
const nameFn = fn1()

// we can now call nameFn with an argument
nameFn(&#39;OJNSim&#39;) // hello OJNSim
```

You can learn more about **closures** here: https://medium.com/javascript-scene/master-the-javascript-interview-what-is-a-closure-b2f0d2152b36

